Structured AI Facilitation for Local Deliberation:

A Formal Model and Theoretical Foundations of the Listen‑Align‑Draft Protocol

Author: ouadi Maakoul 
---

Abstract

Local democratic bodies increasingly face information overload, unequal participation, and low trust in outcomes. Artificial intelligence systems offer new possibilities for structuring deliberation, yet most civic AI tools focus on preference aggregation rather than collective meaning‑making. This thesis develops a formal model of the Listen‑Align‑Draft (LAD) protocol—a structured AI facilitation intervention designed to support group deliberation while preserving human agency and dissenting viewpoints. We introduce mathematically precise definitions for deliberation quality (equality, reciprocity, argument diversity), proposal quality, and trust. The core contribution is a set of formal metrics: the Dissent Preservation Score (DPS), the Semantic Retention Score (R<sub>sem</sub>), and a rubric‑based proposal quality index. We model the AI facilitation function F_{\text{AI}}(U_t) = (S_t, M_t, Q_t) and embed the intervention in a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) that explicates causal pathways from AI support to improved outcomes via cognitive offloading, visualization, equalization of voice, and co‑authorship. We prove key mathematical properties of these metrics—invariance, bounds, and consistency—and provide a theoretical foundation for their use in evaluating AI‑mediated deliberation. The thesis also proposes a rigorous methodological framework for testing the LAD protocol, including randomized controlled trial designs, fidelity measurement, and strategies to isolate the effect of AI from structured facilitation alone. By formalizing the mechanisms and metrics, this work provides a replicable foundation for future empirical research on generative collective intelligence.

