Chapter 2. Literature Review

2.1 Introduction

The Listen‑Align‑Draft (LAD) protocol sits at the intersection of three rich scholarly traditions: deliberative democracy, human‑computer interaction (HCI) and AI‑mediated communication, and group facilitation research. This chapter reviews these literatures to establish the theoretical foundations for the formal model developed in Chapter 3. The review proceeds in four main sections. First, I examine normative theories of deliberative democracy and the empirical study of public participation, focusing on how deliberation is understood and measured. Second, I analyze the specific challenges that local democratic bodies face—process debt, inequality, and trust deficits—and how these have been addressed by traditional facilitation approaches. Third, I survey the emerging landscape of AI tools for civic engagement, distinguishing between preference‑aggregation systems (e.g., Polis, vTaiwan) and collaborative meaning‑making tools. Fourth, I review research on structured facilitation and group cognition, highlighting how formal structures can improve group outcomes. The chapter concludes by synthesizing the gaps that motivate the LAD protocol: the need for a formal model that explicitly preserves dissent, supports collaborative drafting, and articulates causal mechanisms linking AI use to deliberative outcomes.

2.2 Deliberative Democracy and Public Participation

2.2.1 Normative Foundations

Deliberative democracy theory posits that legitimate political decisions arise from public reasoning among free and equal citizens (Habermas, 1996; Cohen, 1989). Unlike aggregative models that reduce democracy to vote counting, deliberation emphasizes the transformation of preferences through exposure to reasons and perspectives. Key normative criteria include inclusivity (all affected should participate), authenticity (participants are sincere and consider others’ arguments), and consequentiality (deliberation influences outcomes) (Dryzek, 2009).

Empirical researchers have operationalized these ideals. Fishkin (2018) developed the deliberative poll, a method that brings a representative sample of citizens together to discuss issues with balanced information. Steiner (2012) proposed the Discourse Quality Index (DQI), which codes deliberation along dimensions such as justification, respect, and counterarguments. Stromer‑Galley (2007) offered a comprehensive coding scheme for measuring deliberation’s content, distinguishing between statements of opinion, justifications, and interactions.

2.2.2 The Local Level as Deliberative Space

Local democratic bodies—neighborhood councils, school boards, participatory budgeting assemblies—are particularly important sites for deliberation. They are often smaller, more accessible, and have direct impact on citizens’ lives (Fung, 2006). Participatory budgeting (PB), pioneered in Porto Alegre, Brazil, has spread globally, demonstrating that structured processes can yield equitable resource allocation (Wampler, 2007). Yet local deliberation also confronts structural constraints: time limitations, power imbalances, and the difficulty of moving from talk to actionable decisions.

2.2.3 Measuring Deliberation Quality

Several frameworks exist to assess deliberation quality. In addition to the DQI, researchers use network analysis to map conversational structure (Schwarz & Stein, 2019), content analysis to identify argument diversity (Mutz, 2006), and surveys to gauge participant perceptions of fairness and trust (Colquitt, 2001). However, many of these measures are labor‑intensive and difficult to scale. The LAD protocol’s AI components (transcription, clustering, summarization) offer potential for automated, real‑time measurement, but this requires careful validation.

2.3 Challenges in Local Deliberation

2.3.1 Process Debt

A perennial complaint about local meetings is that they consume considerable time but produce little concrete output (Aakhus, 2007). The term “process debt” captures the accumulation of meetings, minutes, and unresolved issues without decision closure. This problem is exacerbated by the absence of professional facilitators or note‑takers; often, participants themselves must juggle speaking with recording, which reduces cognitive resources for problem‑solving.

2.3.2 Inequality of Participation

Empirical studies consistently show that in informal meetings, a few individuals dominate the conversation, while others—often women, minorities, or low‑income residents—speak less frequently (Karpowitz & Mendelberg, 2014). Structured turn‑taking and facilitation can mitigate this, but many local bodies lack such structures. The Gini coefficient of utterance counts, which we introduce formally in Chapter 3, provides a precise measure of this inequality.

2.3.3 Trust Deficits

Trust in governmental processes is low in many democracies (Dalton, 2004). In local contexts, trust is closely tied to procedural fairness: whether participants feel they were heard, treated with respect, and that the process was transparent (Tyler, 2006). When proposals emerge from opaque processes—or when participants perceive that their concerns were ignored—trust erodes, reducing willingness to cooperate or accept outcomes.

2.3.4 Traditional Facilitative Interventions

Facilitation techniques such as round‑robin, small‑group breakout discussions, and visual mapping (e.g., “mind maps”) have been shown to improve equality and satisfaction (Schwarz, 2002). However, these methods are resource‑intensive and require skilled facilitators. The LAD protocol attempts to embed similar structures into a technology‑assisted process that can be scaled and replicated.

2.4 AI in Civic Technology

2.4.1 Preference Aggregation Platforms

The most prominent AI‑mediated civic engagement tool is Polis (Small et al., 2021). Polis collects participant statements, uses machine learning to cluster opinions, and produces a map showing where agreement and disagreement lie. The vTaiwan platform used Polis to engage citizens in digital policy deliberation (Hsiao et al., 2018). While Polis effectively scales preference aggregation, it does not generate collaborative proposals; it surfaces consensus but does not help groups draft actionable text. Moreover, its emphasis on consensus may underrepresent dissenting voices—a criticism that aligns with broader concerns about “automated consensus” (Landemore, 2020).

2.4.2 Collaborative Meaning‑Making Tools

A smaller body of work explores AI as a collaborative writing assistant. Kim et al. (2021) developed “Meeting Coach,” an AI that provides real‑time feedback on meeting dynamics, such as speaking time and turn‑taking. Tools like Google’s “Assistive Writing” suggestions in Docs illustrate how AI can aid drafting, but they are not designed for deliberative contexts. The LAD protocol’s “Draft” phase, where the AI produces a proposal based on the group’s discussion, is a novel application of large language models (LLMs) to deliberative writing.

2.4.3 Preservation of Dissent

A recurrent concern in AI‑mediated deliberation is that algorithms, optimized for agreement or efficiency, may suppress minority viewpoints (Mills, 2017). This is sometimes called the “tyranny of the majority” in algorithmic form. The LAD protocol explicitly attempts to counter this by instructing the AI to surface friction points and by measuring dissent preservation (DPS). The DPS construct (Chapter 3) is, to our knowledge, the first formal metric designed to hold AI accountable for representing disagreement.

2.4.4 Human Agency and Automation Bias

When AI systems make recommendations, users may exhibit automation bias—over‑reliance on machine outputs (Skitka et al., 1999). In deliberation, this could mean groups accepting a flawed AI draft without critical review. The LAD protocol emphasizes that the AI serves as a scribe, not a decision‑maker; the retention score (Chapter 3) measures how much groups modify the AI’s output, providing a check on automation bias.

2.5 Structured Facilitation and Group Cognition

2.5.1 Formal Structures for Group Interaction

Research in collaborative learning and group decision‑making has long emphasized the value of structured protocols. Schwarz and Stein (2019) conducted a meta‑analysis showing that structured argumentation tools (e.g., frameworks for constructing arguments) improve learning outcomes and decision quality. Woolley et al. (2010) found that collective intelligence—the ability of a group to perform well across tasks—depends not on individual intelligence but on group processes such as equal turn‑taking and social sensitivity.

2.5.2 Cognitive Offloading

Cognitive offloading refers to the use of external tools to reduce mental workload (Risko & Gilbert, 2016). In meetings, note‑taking serves as offloading; however, it distracts from listening and synthesis. The AI’s transcription and summarization functions in LAD are designed to offload these tasks, freeing cognitive resources for problem‑solving and critical evaluation.

2.5.3 Visualization and Shared Understanding

Visual representations of group discussions—whether concept maps, issue trees, or cluster diagrams—can help participants recognize common ground and divergence (Fischer & Mandl, 2005). The “Align” phase of LAD presents such visualizations, which we hypothesize reduce the time needed to reach shared understanding.

2.5.4 Co‑authorship and Ownership

Research in writing studies suggests that co‑authorship can increase ownership and commitment to the final product (Ede & Lunsford, 1990). When a group collaboratively revises an AI‑generated draft, we anticipate that they will perceive the proposal as “theirs,” enhancing trust in the outcome. The co‑authorship effect is incorporated as a pathway in the causal model (Chapter 3).

2.6 Gaps and the Present Study

The literature reveals several gaps that motivate the LAD protocol and its formal model:

1. Integration of AI into collaborative drafting: While preference‑aggregation platforms exist, there is no formal model for AI‑assisted collaborative proposal generation that explicitly preserves dissent.
2. Lack of formal metrics for dissent preservation and human agency: Existing evaluation frameworks for civic AI focus on efficiency or consensus, not on the fidelity of AI to represent disagreement.
3. Unarticulated causal mechanisms: Most studies compare AI to no‑AI conditions without explicating how AI affects group processes (e.g., equalization, cognitive load). Without a causal model, it is difficult to replicate or improve interventions.
4. Limited attention to facilitator fidelity and AI implementation details: Field studies often treat AI as a black box, ignoring variations in how it is used. The LAD framework includes a structured facilitator log and fidelity measures to address this.

The LAD protocol and the formal model presented in Chapter 3 address these gaps by providing:

· A mathematically precise definition of the AI facilitation function F_{\text{AI}}.
· Novel metrics for dissent preservation (DPS) and human agency (semantic retention).
· A Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) that hypothesizes causal pathways from AI use to outcomes.
· A detailed methodological framework (Chapter 4) that includes fidelity measurement and strategies to isolate the AI effect from structured facilitation alone.

By grounding the intervention in established literatures on deliberation, group cognition, and human‑AI interaction, this thesis contributes a theoretically informed and empirically testable model for AI‑mediated collective meaning‑making.


Chapter 3. Theoretical Framework and Formal Model

3.1 Preliminaries and Notation

Let a deliberative group be a set of participants P = \{p_1, \dots, p_n\} engaging in a facilitated conversation over a fixed problem domain D. The conversation yields a sequence of utterances U = \{u_1, \dots, u_m\}, each associated with a participant p(u_i) \in P and a timestamp t(u_i). Utterances may be responses to previous utterances; we denote the parent–child relation via a discourse parser.

Definition 3.1 (Semantic Embedding).
Let E: \mathcal{U} \to \mathbb{R}^d be a function that maps an utterance to a d-dimensional vector embedding (e.g., from a sentence transformer). The cosine similarity between two utterances is:

\operatorname{sim}(u_i, u_j) = \frac{E(u_i) \cdot E(u_j)}{\|E(u_i)\| \|E(u_j)\|}.

For a set of utterances, we denote their mean embedding as \bar{E}(U) = \frac{1}{|U|}\sum_{u \in U} E(u) and the variance (scatter) as \operatorname{Var}(U) = \frac{1}{|U|}\sum_{u \in U} \|E(u) - \bar{E}(U)\|^2.

3.2 Deliberation Quality Metrics

3.2.1 Equality of Participation.
Let c(p) = \#\{u \in U : p(u) = p\} be the utterance count for participant p. The Gini coefficient of utterance counts is:

G(U) = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^n |c(p_i) - c(p_j)|}{2n \sum_{k=1}^n c(p_k)}.

A lower G(U) indicates more equal participation. G(U) \in [0,1] with 0 corresponding to perfect equality.

3.2.2 Reciprocity.
Let R(U) be the proportion of utterances that are direct replies to previous utterances (as determined by a discourse parser). Formally, if we denote a reply indicator \rho(u_i) = 1 if u_i has a parent utterance in the conversation, and 0 otherwise, then:

\operatorname{Recip}(U) = \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^m \rho(u_i).

3.2.3 Argument Diversity.
We perform semantic clustering using BERTopic or a similar algorithm. For a given cosine similarity threshold \delta \in (0,1), we define a cluster as a maximal set of utterances such that for any two utterances in the cluster there exists a chain of utterances with pairwise similarity \ge \delta. The number of clusters K_{\delta}(U) serves as a proxy for argument diversity.
Limitation: The choice of \delta affects K. We treat \delta as a parameter to be tuned; sensitivity analyses are recommended.

3.3 Proposal Quality and Trust

3.3.1 Proposal Quality Rubric.
An actionable proposal is a structured document specifying problem definition, proposed actions, responsible parties, resources, and success metrics. We define a quality score Q_{\text{prop}} \in [0,12] as the sum of four sub‑dimensions:

Dimension Scoring
Completeness 0–4: one point each for problem definition, proposed actions (≥2), resource allocation, success metrics.
Feasibility 1–4: Likert from “actions impossible” to “timeline and stakeholders specified.”
Inclusivity 1–4: Likert from “single viewpoint” to “integrative complexity balancing conflicting needs.”
Accountability 1–4: Likert from “vague ‘we should’” to “links dissenting views to specific compromise actions.”

The total score is the sum of these four components.

3.3.2 Trust and Fairness.
We adopt established scales:

· Trust T: Mayer & Davis (1999) 8‑item scale (α typically > 0.90). Items measure perceived ability, benevolence, and integrity of the process.
· Procedural Fairness F: Colquitt (2001) scale capturing voice, neutrality, respect, and trustworthiness.

Both are measured post‑session on 7‑point Likert scales and aggregated to group means for analysis.

3.4 AI Facilitation Function

The AI assistant processes the current state of the conversation U_t (up to time t) and produces outputs at scheduled reflection points. Define:

F_{\text{AI}}(U_t) = (S_t, M_t, Q_t),

where:

· S_t: a natural language summary of the discussion so far, focusing on key points and unresolved issues.
· M_t: a visual issue map, typically a semantic cluster diagram with “consensus zones” and “friction points” highlighted.
· Q_t: a set of procedural clarifying questions (e.g., “Would someone like to speak to the budget point?”). Substantive steering questions are prohibited to preserve neutrality.

The AI uses a fixed‑version large language model (e.g., GPT‑4‑0613) with a system prompt that explicitly instructs it to preserve dissent and avoid creating false consensus (see Appendix A for the full prompt).

3.5 Human Agency and Retention

We define two complementary retention scores to capture how much of the AI’s initial draft is adopted by the group.

3.5.1 Character‑Level Retention.
Let D_{\text{AI}} be the initial draft generated by the AI and D_{\text{Final}} the final proposal after group editing. The character‑level Levenshtein distance L(D_{\text{AI}}, D_{\text{Final}}) counts the minimum number of insertions, deletions, and substitutions to transform one into the other. The retention score is:

R_{\text{char}} = 1 - \frac{L(D_{\text{AI}}, D_{\text{Final}})}{\max(|D_{\text{AI}}|, |D_{\text{Final}}|)} \in [0,1].

3.5.2 Semantic Retention.
To better capture preservation of meaning, we compute the cosine similarity between the embeddings of the two documents:

R_{\text{sem}} = \frac{E(D_{\text{AI}}) \cdot E(D_{\text{Final}})}{\|E(D_{\text{AI}})\| \|E(D_{\text{Final}})\|}.

We treat a high R_{\text{sem}} as indicating that the core ideas were retained, even if wording changed. A low R_{\text{sem}} suggests substantive revision.

Proposition 3.1 (Monotonicity of R_{\text{sem}}).
If D_{\text{Final}} is obtained by only adding utterances that are semantically similar to the existing content, then R_{\text{sem}} is non‑decreasing. Proof follows from the triangle inequality of the angle between vectors in embedding space.

3.6 Dissent Preservation Score (DPS)

The AI must not smooth over disagreement. We define two complementary DPS metrics.

3.6.1 Count‑Based DPS.
Let \mathcal{D}_{\text{trans}} be the set of unique dissenting viewpoints in the full transcript, identified via manual coding of a 20% subsample and extended using automated keyword extraction with validation. Let \mathcal{D}_{\text{AI}} be the set of dissenting viewpoints that appear in either the issue map M_t or the initial draft D_{\text{AI}}. Then:

\operatorname{DPS}_{\text{count}} = \frac{|\mathcal{D}_{\text{AI}}|}{|\mathcal{D}_{\text{trans}}|}.

A value near 1 indicates high preservation; values <1 indicate that some dissents were omitted.

3.6.2 Variance‑Based DPS (Polarization Delta).
A more continuous measure captures whether the AI homogenizes the debate. Define:

\Delta_{\text{var}} = \frac{\operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{trans}})}{\operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{AI}})},

where \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{trans}}) is the semantic variance of all utterances in the transcript, and \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{AI}}) is the semantic variance of the utterances in the AI summary or map. A \Delta_{\text{var}} > 1 indicates that the AI has reduced variance (i.e., “flattened” the debate). We interpret \Delta_{\text{var}} close to 1 as good preservation.

Proposition 3.2 (Bound on \Delta_{\text{var}}).
If U_{\text{AI}} is a subset of the utterances in U_{\text{trans}}, then \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{AI}}) \le \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{trans}}) (since variance is maximized over the full set only if the subset is selected to maximize spread). Hence \Delta_{\text{var}} \ge 1 for subsets; however, the AI may produce novel utterances not in the transcript, potentially increasing variance. A bound cannot be given without further assumptions.

3.7 Causal Model and Directed Acyclic Graph

The hypothesized causal pathways are represented in Figure 3.1 (see Appendix B). The DAG includes the following nodes and edges:

· Treatment (LAD): binary indicator.
· Cognitive Offloading: reduced note‑taking burden for participants and facilitators.
· Visualization of Common Ground and Dissent: the issue map M_t makes points of agreement and disagreement explicit.
· Equalization of Voice: the AI cues structured turn‑taking and may reduce dominance.
· Co‑authorship Effect: group co‑creates final proposal with AI as scribe, increasing ownership.
· Time to Proposal: primary outcome.
· Trust (T): post‑session trust in process.
· Fairness (F): perceived procedural fairness.
· Proposal Quality (Q_{\text{prop}}): final proposal score.

Edges:

· Treatment → Cognitive Offloading, Visualization, Equalization of Voice, Co‑authorship.
· Cognitive Offloading → Time to Proposal.
· Visualization → Time to Proposal, Proposal Quality.
· Equalization of Voice → Fairness, Time to Proposal.
· Co‑authorship → Trust.
· Fairness → Trust.

All relationships are subject to baseline covariates (group size, SES, racial composition, facilitator fixed effects). This DAG guides the choice of mediators and the identification strategy for causal mediation analysis.

3.8 Mathematical Properties and Proofs

We collect here several theoretical results that underpin the validity of the proposed metrics.

Lemma 3.1 (Gini Coefficient Invariance).
The Gini coefficient G(U) is invariant under renaming participants and under scaling all utterance counts by a positive constant. Proof: the formula depends only on relative frequencies.

Lemma 3.2 (Semantic Retention as Cosine Similarity).
The cosine similarity R_{\text{sem}} is invariant to scaling of embeddings and lies in [-1,1]. For document embeddings generated from average of utterance embeddings, it is also invariant to permutation of utterances within each document.

Proposition 3.3 (Consistency of Cluster Count).
If the utterances are generated from a mixture of K true topics with embeddings drawn from isotropic Gaussian distributions with distinct means and sufficiently small within‑cluster variance, then as the number of utterances increases, the number of clusters K_{\delta}(U) with \delta chosen between the maximum within‑cluster similarity and the minimum between‑cluster similarity will converge to K with probability 1. (Proof follows from standard results in clustering consistency.)

Proposition 3.4 (Monotonicity of DPS with Respect to Inclusion).
If we add an additional dissenting viewpoint to the AI output, both \operatorname{DPS}_{\text{count}} and \Delta_{\text{var}} (when \Delta_{\text{var}} is defined as the ratio of variances) will move toward 1 (count) or increase (variance), assuming the added utterance increases variance. Formal statement: Let U_{\text{AI}}' = U_{\text{AI}} \cup \{u\} where u is a new utterance not previously in the AI output. Then \operatorname{DPS}_{\text{count}}' \ge \operatorname{DPS}_{\text{count}}. For \Delta_{\text{var}}, if \|E(u) - \bar{E}(U_{\text{AI}})\|^2 > \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{AI}}), then \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{AI}}') > \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{AI}}), hence \Delta_{\text{var}}' = \operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{trans}})/\operatorname{Var}(U_{\text{AI}}') < \Delta_{\text{var}} (i.e., closer to 1 if originally >1). Proof by algebraic manipulation.

These properties ensure that the metrics behave intuitively and are suitable for quantitative evaluation.

